The Problem It Solves

Imagine you’re building something like this:

Shapes: Circle, Rectangle
Colors: Red, Blue

If you combine them the naive way, you get:

RedCircle, BlueCircle
RedRectangle, BlueRectangle

Now scale that up… it explodes. Every new feature multiplies your classes. That’s not design—that’s chaos wearing a suit.

🌉 The Core Idea

Separate:

Abstraction → what the user interacts with (e.g., Shape)
Implementation → how it’s actually done (e.g., Color)

Then connect them with composition instead of inheritance.

🔧 Structure
Abstraction: high-level control (e.g., Shape)
Refined Abstraction: specific versions (e.g., Circle)
Implementor: interface for implementation (e.g., Color)
Concrete Implementor: actual behavior (e.g., Red, Blue)
💻 Example (Java-style)
// Implementor
interface Color {
    void applyColor();
}

// Concrete Implementors
class Red implements Color {
    public void applyColor() {
        System.out.println("Applying red color");
    }
}

class Blue implements Color {
    public void applyColor() {
        System.out.println("Applying blue color");
    }
}

// Abstraction
abstract class Shape {
    protected Color color;

    protected Shape(Color color) {
        this.color = color;
    }

    abstract void draw();
}

// Refined Abstraction
class Circle extends Shape {
    public Circle(Color color) {
        super(color);
    }

    public void draw() {
        System.out.print("Drawing Circle with ");
        color.applyColor();
    }
}

class Rectangle extends Shape {
    public Rectangle(Color color) {
        super(color);
    }

    public void draw() {
        System.out.print("Drawing Rectangle with ");
        color.applyColor();
    }
}
🚀 Usage
Shape redCircle = new Circle(new Red());
Shape blueRectangle = new Rectangle(new Blue());

redCircle.draw();
blueRectangle.draw();